SIMPLE: twilight
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Twilight
<hw>Twi"light`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>twilight</ets>, AS. <ets>twi-</ets> (see <er>Twice</er>) +
<ets>le⟦oacute⟧ht</ets> light; hence the sense of doubtful or half
light; cf. LG. <ets>twelecht</ets>, G. <ets>zwielicht</ets>. See
<er>Light</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The light perceived before the rising, and after the
setting, of the sun, or when the sun is less than 18⟦deg⟧ below the
horizon, occasioned by the illumination of the earth's atmosphere by the
direct rays of the sun and their reflection on the earth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>faint light; a dubious or uncertain medium through
which anything is viewed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As when the sun . . . from behind the moon,⟦br⟧
In dim eclipse, disastrous <qex>twilight</qex> sheds.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>twilight</qex> of probability.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twilight</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Twilight
<hw>Twi"light`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Seen or done by
twilight.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Imperfectly illuminated; shaded; obscure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O'er the <qex>twilight</qex> groves and dusky caves.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twill</ent>⟦br⟧
